The concept of ''machishū'' is a continuation of earlier urban groups such as the {{ill|Kyowarawa|ja|京童|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and later evolved into the {{ill|Chōnin|ja|町人|qq=draft|qq=draft}} class during the early modern {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

Today, it is commonly pronounced as "machishū," but contemporary historical sources such as the {{ill|Setsuyōshū|ja|節要集|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Nippo Jisho|ja|日葡辞書|qq=draft|qq=draft}} suggest that it was pronounced as "chōshū."
