{{Unreferenced|date=July 2017}}
'''Machishū''' (町衆) refers to the wealthy merchants and craftsmen of {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto|qq=}} from the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] to the {{ill|Sengoku period (Japan)|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period (Japan)|qq=}}, particularly those involved with {{ill|Dozō|ja|土倉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dozō|qq=}}. They were an important social class in the reconstruction of Kyoto after the [[:en:Ōnin War|Ōnin War]]. They promoted self-governance, unity, and the development of culture, primarily practicing faith in the [[:en:Lotus Sutra|Lotus Sutra]]. Their central temple was [[:en:Honnō-ji|Honnō-ji]].

The concept of ''machishū'' is a continuation of earlier urban groups such as the {{ill|Kyowarawa|ja|京童|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyowarawa|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} of the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]] and later evolved into the [[:en:Chōnin|Chōnin]] class during the early modern [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]].

Today, it is commonly pronounced as "machishū," but contemporary historical sources such as the {{ill|Setsuyōshū|ja|節要集|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Setsuyōshū|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and the [[:en:Nippo Jisho|Nippo Jisho]] suggest that it was pronounced as "chōshū."
